  fiTitle: "Tiedon jyvi\xE4"
  fiDesc: "Hausj\xE4rvi"
  fiIntroText: "Sirja Untamontyt\xE4r S\xE4is\xE4 l\xF6ydettiin mets\xE4st\xE4 harhailemasta
    pirkkalaisten mets\xE4stysretken j\xE4lkeen. Pian talossa, jonka suojiin nuori
    tytt\xF6 otettiin, havaittiin, ett\xE4 tytt\xF6 osasi k\xE4ytt\xE4\xE4 majavanhaustaa
    taitavasti l\xE4\xE4kkeen\xE4. Tytt\xF6 osasi my\xF6s myyd\xE4 haustaa tarvitsijalle
    hyv\xE4ll\xE4 hinnalla. H\xE4n rikastutti vaatimatonta torppaa, jonka suojiin
    h\xE4net oli otettu ja vastasi hyv\xE4ll\xE4 hyv\xE4ntekij\xF6illeen. \t\r\n\r\nV\xE4hitellen
    Sirja kasvoi aikuiseksi, piti osan taidoistaan vain omana tietonaan, vaikka menikin
    naimisiin talon vanhimman pojan kanssa. H\xE4n kehittyi kuuluisaksi tiet\xE4j\xE4ksi
    ja taitajaksi, ja talo vaurastui h\xE4nen ansiostaan.\t\r\nSirjalla oli monta
    taitoa k\xE4siss\xE4\xE4n. H\xE4n osasi my\xF6s leipoa leip\xE4\xE4, jota parempaa
    kulkijat eiv\xE4t koskaan olleet saaneet. H\xE4n opetti leiv\xE4n teon vain tytt\xE4rilleen
    ja vannotti paljastamaan salaisuuden vain omille tytt\xE4rilleen. \r\n\r\nSirjalla
    oli tiedon jyv\xE4, joka vaikutti pitk\xE4lle tulevaisuuteen\u2026\r"
  fiOutroText: "\u201DViel\xE4k\xF6 Sirjan sukuisia l\xF6ytyy t\xE4\xE4lt\xE4?\u201D
    Kysyi kulkija osuessaan S\xE4is\xE4n vanhaan taloon Hausj\xE4rvell\xE4.\r\n\u201DEik\xF6h\xE4n
    lie kaikki t\xE4\xE4ll\xE4 samasta kanta\xE4idist\xE4\u201D, vastasi vanha nainen
    tuvan tulisijan vierest\xE4, kiikkustuolista. \r\nSiin\xE4 h\xE4n istuu kuin
    Niskavuoren Loviisa, selv\xE4sti talon vanha em\xE4nt\xE4, ajatteli mies ja laski
    reppunsa lattialle. Tuvassa tuoksui tuore leip\xE4. Isot kakot oli peitetty leivinliinoilla.\r\n\u201DSaisikohan
    sit\xE4 ev\xE4st\xE4 ostaa, olen mets\xE4\xE4n menossa, mutta ei sattunut kauppaa
    matkan varrelle, ajattelin t\xE4\xE4lt\xE4 kysy\xE4.\u201D\r\nVanha em\xE4nt\xE4
    kampesi itsens\xE4 pystyyn, otti ison vaalean kakon, ja k\xE4\xE4r\xE4isi sen
    voipaperin sis\xE4\xE4n.\r\n\u201DKyll\xE4 kulkija aina leiv\xE4n saa, sellainen
    on ollut talon tapa, aina Sirjan ajoista asti. Kaivolta sopii vett\xE4\r\nottaa.
    Tai navetalta hakea pullo maitoa.\u201D\r\nMies oli n\xE4hnyt pihassa ison, vanhan
    kivinavetan. H\xE4n kiitteli, t\xE4ytti pullonsa kaivolla ja k\xE4veli mets\xE4\xE4n.
    M\xE4elle kiivetty\xE4\xE4n h\xE4n k\xE4\xE4ntyi katsomaan taakseen, vaan eip\xE4
    ollut n\xE4k\xF6piiriss\xE4 yht\xE4\xE4n sellaista taloa, jossa h\xE4n oli k\xE4ynyt.
    Leip\xE4 ja vesipullo kuitenkin repussa.\r"
  enTitle: Crump of knowledge
  enDesc: "Hausj\xE4rvi"
  enIntroText: "Sirja S\xE4is\xE4, daughter of Untamo, was found wandering in the
    forest after a hunting trip by the Birka people. Soon, the people who had given
    shelter to the young girl discovered that she used beaver castoreum for medication
    skilfully. She also knew how to sell castoreum to those who needed it and how
    to make a nice profit. She paid it forward and helped the modest house to become
    wealthy. \t\r\nSirja grew up, keeping some of her skills only to herself, even
    when she married the oldest son of the house. She became a renowned seer and
    healer, helping the house become affluent.\t\r\nSirja had skilful hands. Her
    bread tasted better than anything that the people passing by had ever tasted.
    She only taught her own daughters how to bake the bread, making them pledge they
    would only share the secret with their own daughters. \r\n\r\nSirja held a crumb
    of knowledge that had long-term impact...\r"
  enOutroText: "\u201CAre there still Sirja\u2019s relatives here?\u201D a traveller
    asked when visiting the old S\xE4is\xE4 house in Hausj\xE4rvi.\r\n\"I figure
    we all have the same ancestress\", answered the lady who was sitting in a rocking
    chair next to the fireplace. \r\nShe is a real matron, sitting there, clearly
    a widow who once used to run the house, the man thought and put his rucksack
    on the floor. The smell of freshly baked bread was wafting into the room, and
    big loaves had been covered with tea towels.\r\n\u201CIs it possible to buy something
    to eat? I am headed to the forest, but there were no shops on the way, so I thought
    I would ask you\u201D.\r\nThe matron stood up, grabbed a big loaf of bread and
    wrapped it inside greaseproof paper.\r\n\"A traveller is always given a loaf
    at this house, that is how we have done it from Sirja\u2019s days. You can take
    water from the well.\r\nOr a bottle of milk from the cowshed.\u201D\r\nOutside,
    the man had seen a big, old cowshed that was built of stone. He said his thanks,
    filled his bottle at the well and walked into the forest. After climbing up the
    hill, he turned to look back. But he could no longer see the house he had visited.
    The bread and the bottle of water were still in his rucksack, though.\r"
